Additionally, the study established increased production of proteins known as chemokines, whose role is to attract inflammatory immune cells in the lungs and lung blood vessels.
In particular, genes for chemokines such as CCR2 (chemokine receptor 2) were over expressed in critically ill patients and so, such had unusual influx of macrophages in the lungs, leading to pulmonary inflammation, which led to reduced capacity of the lungs to allow diffusion of oxygen.
 The patients suffer hypoxiaemic symptoms and die from insufficient supply of oxygen. Treatment of such patients with anti-CCR2 monoclonal antibodies greatly improved the lung capacity and restored oxygen levels.
People with symptoms should be subjected to genetic testing to determine if they have genes for propensity to critical illness so as to put them in treatments that will prevent the disease from advancing to moderate, then to severe level associated with high mortality rates.
